Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Trim the @butternut squash{1}(trimmed and diced) into 1cm chunks. Pop the diced butternut onto a
large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{}, season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{},
sprinkle over the @roasted spice and herb blend{1%sachet}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a
single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Meanwhile, bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with 1/2 tsp of @salt{1/2%tsp} for the
@macaroni{180%g}.

When the oven is hot, roast the butternut on the top shelf until golden and cooked through,
~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

When your water is boiling, stir the macaroni into the pan and bring back to the boil.
Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back into the pan. Drizzle with @olive oil{} and
stir through to stop it sticking together.

While everything cooks, pick the @sage{1%bunch} leaves from their stalks and finely chop
(discard the stalks).

== Sage Panko Crumb ==

In a #small bowl{}, combine the sage, @panko breadcrumbs{25%g} and @olive oil{2%tbsp} for the
crumb. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, then set aside your sage crumb.

Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{60%g}(grated).

== Cheese Sauce ==

Melt the @butter{20%g} in another large saucepan on medium-high heat. Once hot, stir in the
@plain flour{1.5%tbsp}. Cook until it forms a paste, ~{1-2%minutes} - you've made a roux!

Stir in the @water{200%ml} a little at a time, followed by the @vegetable stock paste{10%g}.
Bring to the boil, stir and simmer until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir in the
@creme fraiche{150%g}, then remove from the heat.

Add the @dijon mustard{10%g}, @hard Italian style cheese{20%g}(grated) and Cheddar. Stir until
combined and melted. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

> Add less mustard if you don't love mustard.

== Assembly ==

When the butternut is ready, remove it from the oven and turn your grill on to high.

Stir the butternut into the sauce along with the cooked macaroni. Add a splash of water if
it's a little thick. Taste and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed.

Transfer the pasta to an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}. Sprinkle over the sage crumb,
then pop it under the grill until golden and bubbling, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When ready, share the butternut squash mac and cheese between your serving bowls and get
stuck in.

> Enjoy!